@afgonzal In my case, I only need to worry about sort ordering of the rows and not filtering.  However, I suspect that the same approach I use to handle ordering could be adapted to handle filtering.  Basically, I just use the smart table controller methods to interrogate the present tableState.  This in combination with knowing something about the 'new' record I inserted (for example knowing that it is either the last or first row in the data set), allows me to determine which page of the data should contain the row.  I then use the stCtrl.slice method to position the table properly to contain the desired page.  The only trick here may be making sure that you are making these checks and position alteration in the subsequent digest cycle (via $timwout or other similar technique), so that the addition of the row in the preceding cycle has had a chance to be rendered.  A final optional step, may be to locate and focus an input in the target new row once the proper page has been sliced.  I do this with traditional angular.element methods to 'find' and focus the proper element.  The below is not pretty, but functional; I'd welcome your thoughts as well for improvement!

`
					scope.data.push({
						id: -((new Date()).getTime()),
						quantity: 0,
						costPerUnit: 0.00,
						totalCost: 0.00
					});

					$timeout(function() {	// need to get to next digest cycle to allow table to be updated first
						// Need to get to correct page in table?
						//console.log('Pages: ' + scope.tableState.pagination.numberOfPages + ' ' + scope.tableState.pagination.number)
						if (scope.tableState.pagination.numberOfPages > 1) {
							if (! scope.tableState.sort.predicate) {
								// table is not sorted, just go to last page
								scope.stCtrl.slice((scope.tableState.pagination.numberOfPages - 1) * scope.tableState.pagination.number, scope.tableState.pagination.number);
							} else {
								if (scope.tableState.sort.predicate === quantityAttribute ||
								 	scope.tableState.sort.predicate === costAttribute ||
									scope.tableState.sort.predicate === extendedAttribute) {
									// these values are defaulted to zero and will be pushed to the first row when reverse is false,
									// so push to first page then, otherwise push to last page
									scope.stCtrl.slice((! scope.tableState.sort.reverse) ? 0 : (scope.tableState.pagination.numberOfPages - 1) * scope.tableState.pagination.number, scope.tableState.pagination.number);
								} else {
									// everything else should be on last page
									scope.stCtrl.slice(scope.tableState.sort.reverse ? 0 : (scope.tableState.pagination.numberOfPages - 1) * scope.tableState.pagination.number, scope.tableState.pagination.number);
								}
							}
						}

						// Focus first element in new row
						$timeout(function() {	// need to get to next digest cycle to allow table to be updated with new page
							var table = element.find('#' + scope.component.name + 'EstimateTable');
							//console.log(scope.component.name + 'EstimateTable ' + table + ' ' + table.length);
							var tbody = table.children('tbody');
							// Row to highlight may be first or last on page depending upon sort order
							var row;
							if (Object.getOwnPropertyNames(scope.tableState.sort).length === 0) {
								// forward search
								row = tbody.children('tr').length - 1;
							} else {
								if (scope.tableState.sort.predicate === quantityAttribute ||
									scope.tableState.sort.predicate === costAttribute ||
									scope.tableState.sort.predicate === extendedAttribute) {
									row = ! scope.tableState.sort.reverse ? 0 : tbody.children('tr').length - 1;
								} else {
									row = ! scope.tableState.sort.reverse ? tbody.children('tr').length - 1 : 0;
								}
							}
							var tr = angular.element(tbody.children('tr')[row]);
							var td = tr.children('td');
							var opener = angular.element(td[1]).children('div'); // first td is delete row icon, so skip to 2nd
							angular.element(opener.find('.fa-toggle-down')).trigger('click');
							scope.editFocus = {
								row: row,
								cell: 0
							}
						}, 0);
					}, 0);
`

