@atrauzzi SAS keys are used to give other users, who wouldn't otherwise have access, fine-tuned permissions. If you want to give someone full-blown control, give them the account key instead(make sure you really want them to have full write permissions). If this is for your own personal use and you have the privileges, as travis mentioned, you do not need to specify any further authentication arguments; we will query the account corresponding to the name specified, grab a account key, and use that in the operation.

@ddavtian It looks like the issue you're running into here is that when you call get_secret you're passing an invalid version 1:

    print(client.get_secret(KEY_VAULT_URI, 'octo-prroton', 1))

if you want to get the latest version of the secret you should specify version_none or '':

    print(client.get_secret(KEY_VAULT_URI, 'octo-prroton', KeyVaultId.version_none))

or if you want the specific version you just created you'll need to get it from the secret_bundle:

    print(client.get_secret(KEY_VAULT_URI, 'octo-prroton', SecretId(secret_bundle.id).version))

