You'd probably want to call ``/_matrix/client/r0/login`` as-is to get the login flows beforehand which would be another function. *However*, the same cannot be said for registration. It doesn't appear to give any indication of what flows are supported. 

To clarify on my idea, you'd call begin_login([flowset],callback) with the callback working something like:

begin_login(["password"], callback)

```python3
def callback(stage):
    if stage.type == "password":
         return {user,password}
    else if stage.type == "captcha":
         code = display_captcha(stage)
         return {code}
    throw HelpMe()
```

So I'd be more inclined to provide a single callback which deals with every type of stage.

@brianjmurrell While --dns tunels all DNS requests, --ns-hosts only tunels DNS requests going out to the specified servers.

Let's say example.com is a domain resolving in your remote network and 192.168.100.254 is the DNS server of your remote network.

```
zone "example.com" IN {
	type forward;
	forwarders port 12300 { 192.168.100.254; };
};
```

Launching sshuttle with 
```
$ sshuttle -r user@server --ns-hosts=192.168.100.254
```
will tunel DNS requests of *.example.com via sshuttle and let others resolve normally.

