@shyuep says: "My proposal is simply to treat files as a special data type that gets moved between Fireworks, with a proper language to specify what files are expected and provided by each FireWork."

I have no objections to a proposal that improves the file passing procedures in FireWorks. But, someone needs to fully design it (e.g., the "proper language") and code it. I don't have room in my schedule or that of my group, so you would need recruit someone to do it. I've put it in my "someday" list of things to do, but honestly that is likely not going to happen.

@shyuep asks: "What is accomplished by glue tasks that is not accomplished by inserting an additional Firework?"

You could insert an additional Firework, but glue tasks give you the option of putting it in an existing FW or inserting a new Firework (e.g., with the glue task in it). I imagine most people (including myself) would prefer to put in an existing FW since a new FW means that in some launch modes (e.g., qlaunch singleshot) you would use an entire queued job to just run that one data processing step. Thus the task is better than an additional data processing FW.

@montoyjh says: " My approach previously was simply to add two optional keyword arguments to Workflow.append_wf"

Yes, after sending the comment I had the same thought as well. It's better to just add the functionality to the existing append_wf, there is no need to have two functions to append_wf.

I am closing this PR since we decided to put the function in FWS, and any further discussion of file passing functionality defaulted in FWS should really go to that repo rather than atomate.

