Finally got some time to try this out. I had to modify your code a bit (`resolver` method was being overridden by `Field` in it's init, and you can't use `partial` on class methods), but in general it works exactly as I wanted.

For anyone reading this in the future, this is what I ended up doing:

```python
from functools import partial

import third_party.python3.graphene as graphene


class ProtoEnum(graphene.Field):
    """Provides a link between protobuf enums and GraphQL fields"""

    def __init__(self, protobuf_enum, *args, **kwargs):
        super(ProtoEnum, self).__init__(graphene.Int, *args, **kwargs)
        self.protobuf_enum = protobuf_enum

    def get_resolver(self, parent_resolver):
        return partial(_enum_resolver, self.protobuf_enum, parent_resolver)


def _enum_resolver(protobuf_enum, parent_resolver, root, args, context, info):
    resolved_value = parent_resolver(root, args, context, info)

    if resolved_value not in protobuf_enum.values():
        raise ValueError('Enum value "%s" is invalid' % resolved_value)

    return resolved_value
```

So thank you very much for the help!

@bhack could you explain the motivation for this change?  I believe by default the text plugin will use the TENSORS entry from DEFAULT_SIZE_GUIDANCE which is also 10, so this change would seem to be a no-op.

Also, I think to get the tests to pass you would need to add a dependency on the text_plugin to the application build target here:
