@jskeet, I believe this is mostly for Gapic namespace only. gRPC namespace for tracing is actually `google.devtools.clouderrorreporting.v1` and that's not going to change, while Gapic can choose a slightly different name space (we do that for pubsub already -- gRPC is `google.pubsub.v1` while Gapic is under `Google::Cloud::Pubsub::V1` in Ruby).

Having said that, apparently this will be highly language dependent. Rubyists seem to prefer camelcase for the name space, so it's great we could do that and that's why this PR was created. If people in the language community don't care much, I think one-word 'errorreporting' (and 'Errorreporting' when capitalized) is just fine.

For Node.JS, it could be `@google-cloud/error-reporting`, but I am not sure how many people would care. Until someone raises voice on this topic, I'd like to keep this as-is for now.

Hi @lozino - you can fix the axis by providing both `xtickmin` and `xtickmax` options to the plot (for the x axis for example). You have to provide both as plotly requires a range to display over. (If setting those initially is still updating the plot you may also need to provide these during your append as well, but I don't think that should be required.)

For log axis, you can supply direct plotly opts using the `layoutopts` option. The format for that will be a dict that contains a `plotly` key with the value being a dict of plotly options. The one for using log axis is [here](https://plot.ly/javascript/log-plot/). Note that as this is directly overriding the axis options, the above note about specifying the range may be overridden. If it is, you will need to directly supply the range in the `plotly` dict as a `range` entry containing a two element array with the first being the min and the second being the max, as well as providing `autorange: False`. 

Below is an example that both sets the range and the plot type to log:
```
opts = {
  'layoutopts': {
    'plotly': {
      'xaxis': {
        'type': 'log',
        'range': [0, 1000],
        'autorange': False,
      }
    }
  }
}
```

